[Event] Author: OSINTAgent, Type: Event, Final: False, Partial: None, Content: parts=[Part(
  function_response=FunctionResponse(
    id='adk-e092256a-53fa-411f-bd36-a10200e89214',
    name='search',
    response={
      'result': """A critical Remote Code Execution (RCE) vulnerability, identified as CVE-2024-4577, has been discovered in PHP, primarily affecting Windows installations running PHP in CGI mode. This vulnerability allows attackers to achieve RCE by exploiting how PHP processes command-line arguments, specifically through the manipulation of `allow_url_include` and `auto_prepend_file` directives.

The core of the vulnerability lies in a "best-fit" Unicode processing feature on Windows. When PHP is operating in CGI mode, a soft hyphen (0xAD) in a URL query string is interpreted by PHP as a regular hyphen (0x2D), while the CGI handler fails to properly escape it. This allows an attacker to inject arbitrary command-line arguments into the PHP process.

Attackers leverage this argument injection to dynamically set PHP configuration directives:
*   **`allow_url_include=1`**: This directive, when enabled, permits PHP to include files from remote URLs.
*   **`auto_prepend_file=php://input`**: This directive forces PHP to execute the content of the HTTP POST request body as a PHP script before the main script of the application.

By combining these, an attacker can send a specially crafted HTTP request containing the soft hyphen to inject the `allow_url_include=1` and `auto_prepend_file=php://input` arguments. Subsequently, any malicious PHP code placed in the POST request body will be executed on the server, leading to RCE.

This vulnerability primarily impacts Windows systems with PHP configured in CGI mode, particularly those running with Traditional Chinese (Code Page 950), Simplified Chinese (Code Page 936), or Japanese (Code Page 932) locales. However, researchers caution that other locales might also be vulnerable. Default installations of XAMPP on Windows are known to be susceptible.

To mitigate this vulnerability, it is crucial to update PHP to patched versions (8.3.8, 8.2.20, 8.1.29, or newer). Other recommended security measures include disabling PHP CGI mode, ensuring `allow_url_include` is set to `Off` in the PHP configuration, implementing strict access controls on the web server, and deploying a Web Application Firewall (WAF)."""
    }
  )
)] role='user'
